d.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 315<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 8:55:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> Is this the answer to the power crisis?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Edited to fix broken posticon  -Z</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A> at: 3/26/02 4:16:48 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 9:19:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> What did you have in mind?  Solar Powered Satellite system in orbit<br>
that microwave beams the power to receiving stations on Earth?  Would<br>
be prohibitively expensive to build with current launch costs... if<br>
nuclear powered rockets could lower the launch costs drastically then<br>
it might be feasible... would depend on how such a strong microwave<br>
beam would interact with the atmosphere and environment...<br>
<br>
&quot;EcoWackie Newsflash... an endangered species of bird is now believed<br>
extinct after the last remaining flock flew through the microwave beam<br>
transmitted from the Tesla SPS station in Earth orbit today... I guess<br>
you could say their goose was cooked.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 143<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 10:19:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> The beam wouldn't be strong enough to kill any birds that fly through it.<br>
<br>
Some small birds might actually stay in the beam during winter because it would warm them up a little, just like the people who stand in front of radar dishes to keep warm. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 347<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/02 5:47:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> True. The microwave will probably be spread out as much as a kilometre or more on reaching the surface of Earth. It's a wasteful process. Solar power cells convert photons to electricity, electricity gets converted to microwaves, microwaves get converted at reciever back to electricity then finally to whatever kinetic or heat energy it is required for in the home.<br>
<br>
On the plus side it is free power. Once you pay off the cells. Ideally, we would build them from space resources in the first place. Just take the industrial infrastructure and difficult to manufacture items with us by rocket. <br>
<br>
Could the massive arrays be placed in a solar orbit which avoids debris? Micrmeteoroid impacts could devastate such a programme. Otherwise the panels might be expected to last many decades. There's no reason why all Earth's power couldn't be supplied in this fashion. No ugly windmills or solar panels taking away the beauty of our natural environment. No need to clutter rooftops and every other square inch of space we can locate. We just build massive arrays in space measuring many kilometres in length.<br>
<br>
Ofcourse, it might be prudent having nuclear power plants as 'backup generators' should something disastrous happen. Say, an Asteroid swarm turns the power grid off at the source. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/02 1:12:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> True. The microwave will probably be spread out as much as a kilometre or more on reaching the surface of Earth.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Probably a lot larger.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It's a wasteful process. Solar power cells convert photons to electricity, electricity gets converted to microwaves, microwaves get converted at reciever back to electricity then finally to whatever kinetic or heat energy it is required for in the home.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
63% DC-DC efficency is pretty good although the total efficency when you factor in the PV panels is much lower then that.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Could the massive arrays be placed in a solar orbit which avoids debris?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There really aren't that many things that would hit it in space.  It'll probably lose less then 1% of it's power per decade by hits and even then it's a trival job to repair the damage.  Just replace the broken cell.  Also cover the panels in glass so they don't get destroyed by radiation.<br>
<br>
Only problem is that SPS would be useless if our anti-nuclear group somehow succeeds <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 396<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/02 8:53:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.website-wisdom.com/graphics/icons/simpsons/town/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> What about other sources of electricity 'not of this Earth'?<br>
<br>
Hydrocarbons are abundant. So are other volatiles. Would it be worthwhile making electricity with large generators for similar transmission to Earth? Could we tap into any other source of energy and turn it to electricity. What about the massive volcanic activity of Io or the storms of Jupiter. The universe is a pretty violent place and violence requires energy.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umcullen23456.showPublicProfile?language=EN>mcullen23456</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 6:40:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space</span><hr size=1>   What is the sense of converting the sun's power to <br>
electricity and THEN trying to figure out a way to transmit it down for usage efficiently? We have the capabilities to take a fraction of light and create laser beams, don't we? Apply that basic concept to a satellite ... harvest the unfiltered solar energy from outside our atmosphere, convert it to a concentrated beam aimed at a set of solar panels at the ground level. There would obviously have to be modifications to the panels themselves - I don't believe the current designs would be applicable to higher intensity light sources.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 389<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 10:37:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space</span><hr size=1> You get better efficency using microwaves allowing a smaller satellite.  They're also a lot easier to aim.  Besides solar cells wouldn't be able to take the power of a laser beam and if they could the beam would be very big and the cells would have to be very large.  So large in fact that they'd cost a lot of money.  Rectenas are quite cheap because they're just long wires with about a cm distance between them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 95<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/20/02 2:24:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=158.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> As C.P. Snow states in Two Cultures:<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    The only weapon we have to oppose the bad effects of technology is technology itself. There is no other. We can't retreat into a nontechnological Eden which never existed... It is only by the rational use of technology -- to control and guide what technology is doing --that we can keep any hopes of a social life more desirable than our own; or in face of a social life which is not appauling to imagine.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (Cited by Frederick A. Koomanoff, U.S. Dept. of Energy, in the Summary document of the SPS Program Review.)<br>
 -borrowed from<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.permanent.com/intro.htm"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.permanent.com/logo-permanent.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <br>
</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   &gt;&gt; harvest the unfiltered solar energy from outside<br>
our atmosphere, convert it to a concentrated beam<br>
aimed at a set of solar panels at the ground level.<br>
&gt;<br>
&gt; Rectenas are quite cheap because they're just<br>
long wires with about a cm distance between them.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 The conversion to microwaves at the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.permanent.com/p-sps-ps.htm">SPS</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and back to electricity at the ground is much more efficient than powering a laser. There are still proposals to use lasers, so it's not out of consideration, but seems to need more work.<br>
<br>
&gt; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   63% DC-DC efficency is pretty good although<br>
the total efficency when you factor in the PV panels<br>
is much lower then that.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 For the sake of discussion, it should be noted that whatever we use, the only place efficiency matters is on the ground. If the upper end is horrendously wasteful, then just add more area to the collector. Just so long as the end use on the ground isn't too wasteful.<br>
 It's also interesting that the figure of 63% is what's been achieved in tests of wireless power transmission (WPT). This was done with haphazard equipment, hardly optimized for efficiency. (No, you don't use the microwaves to boil water to turn generators!?!?!)<br>
 It should also be noted that some of the later NASA studies identified closed cycle turbines as the best candidates. Even with the moving parts, the mass savings were worth it.<br>
<br>
&gt;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    Would be prohibitively expensive to build<br>
with current launch costs...</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   1)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> you don't lift the entire SPS system from the ground; you lift <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://permanent.com/i-bootst.htm">seed factories</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> which build bigger factories from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://permanent.com/i-index.htm">space resources</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> as the transportation infrastructure grows to allow large-scale space resources use. (build the tools to build bigger tools to build factories. More than 95% of the factories can be built up this way. More than 98% of the SPS is simple dumb things which can be built in space.)<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Even if you lift a lot of stuff, you don't use the Shuttle or the most expensive ELVs available. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/shuttlec.htm">Shuttle-C</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> or equivalent HLVs would suffice to lift the seeds, and launch costs are amortized over the project, so when it starts paying off from space revenues, launch costs are irrelevant. Space doesn't have to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   cost</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> money. Space can <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   make</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> money.<br>
<br>
&gt;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    would depend on how such a strong microwave<br>
beam would interact with the atmosphere and<br>
environment...</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Just a hunch, but a qualified engineer would probably pick a beam to which the atmosphere is transparent. This necessarily means that there is no interaction with the atmosphere.<br>
 As for birds;<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   1)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The strength of the beam is weak. It would take hours of hovering in the beam to raise body temp by a few 10ths of a degree.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The wavelength is what matters. You don't use a wavelength which would even notice a bird's body size, unless the bird is several tens of meters across (in which case, the metal skin of the &quot;bird&quot; reflects the beam...)<br>
<br>
 Nice serendipity: the ideal wavelength for coming down through the atmosphere is far beyond harming a bird, airplane, metal dental appliances, cities, or anything else. It seems that the only problem would be certain RF appliances which use similar freqs. They'd have to be sited away from where a beam is coming down, or the freqs would have to be shuffled around.<br>
<br>
 Back to &quot;large metal birds&quot;, and an ideal use for SPS power; SPS in GEO send power beams to LEO satellites which fire lasers down to high altitude cruising planes. Lasers heat air, which creates thrust (replacing most of the jet fuel planes use for cruise). Planes run cleaner since they're using only 10% of the fuel they use today, planes carry much less fuel, making take-off safer since they're not so heavy and carrying hundreds of tons of flammable fuels. Planes get smaller since they're not carrying fuels, thus increasing safety even more. Alternately, planes could get <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  much</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bigger, for the same fuel loads.<br>
 No, the beams can't fry cities; they're tuned to hit high flying airplanes which are cooperating in being hit. Most likely, they're not in a freq or power density which could harm anything on the ground.<br>
<br>
Another idea for power use on the ground, is to send power to near-off shore rectennae. Crack H2 from sea water, to mix with atmospheric CO2 to maake CH4 (ntural gas or methane) fuel for shipment &amp; sale. Infrastructure for CH4 exists today, and this takes CO2 right out of the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
&gt;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    Is this the answer to the power crisis?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Not immediately, but after space industries are in place and making money and building up the infrastructure, then it'll <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://permanent.com/p-sps-bt.htm">come to attention for other things</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Eventually, it'll be the primary source of power on Earth, as well as in space.<br>
 This is most likely, though there's always the possibility that somebody will build a pilot plant to proof the technology, thus attracting attention to it.<br>
 It just makes too much sense not to be the eventual main source of power. The Sun is basically eternally free &amp; clean, and industries in space are the only way a big technological civilization can survive. The 2 go together.<br>
<br>
 On the ground, (for large scale power) nuclear has to have its place. Eventually, breeders, MOX, and the entire fuel cycle has to be closed. Nuclear can also pave the way to space resources use, and when the Earth is powered &amp; fed from space resources (not importing food, but wealth and some asteroid metals), space resources may allow us to switch off the last ground power station, after the last factory has closed down.<br>
 The &quot;Green revolution&quot; will allow the Earth to be a garden like it was before we started &quot;raping the planet&quot;. All the industry will be &quot;behind the scenes&quot; or actually, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   above it</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->...<br>
